  </keywords>
  <body>
    <header>
      <para styleclass="Heading1">Executing</para>
    </header>
    <para styleclass="Normal">Beyond the basic launch (see Launching EmulatR), a few run scenarios come up often. All are launched from the Emulatr root and write diagnostics to a redirected log.</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading2">Traced boot</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">Turn on the device trace channels and put the console on an alternate port (so it coexists with another instance). PuTTY follows <text styleclass="Code Example">EMULATR_CONSOLE_PORT</text>.</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">EMULATR_NO_AUTOLOAD=1 EMULATR_CONSOLE_PORT=10024 \</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"> EMULATR_IDE_TRACE=1 EMULATR_IIC_TRACE=1 EMULATR_FLASH_TRACE=1 \</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"> ./out/build/release/Emulatr.exe \</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"> --firmware firmware/ds10_v7_3.exe --autosnapshot off 2&gt; run_ide.log</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading2">Unattended (overnight) run</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">Use <text styleclass="Code Example">nohup</text> so the run survives logoff; leave autosnapshot on and mirror the console to the log.</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">nohup env EMULATR_NO_AUTOLOAD=1 EMULATR_CONSOLE_SNAPSHOT=1 \</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"> EMULATR_CONSOLE_MIRROR=1 EMULATR_CONSOLE_PORT=10023 \</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"> ./out/build/relwithdebinfo/Emulatr.exe --firmware firmware/ds10_v7_3.exe \</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"> &gt; run_overnight.log 2&gt;&amp;1 &amp;</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
    <para styleclass="Heading2">Harvest the slowest console phases</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal">After a run with the console mirrored to the log, the slowest timestamped phases fall out of the log with:</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example">grep -a &apos;\[CON&apos; boot.log \</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"> | sed -E &apos;s/.*\[CON [^+]*\+ *([0-9.]+) ms\] ?/\1\t/&apos; \</para>
    <para styleclass="Code Example"> | sort -rn | head -25</para>
    <para styleclass="Normal"></para>
